For Ponto-Caspian gammarids, the evidence for biological control is minimal. Only one replicated laboratory study in Canada found that an introduced parasitic mould reduced populations of an invasive shrimp (Action ID: 1089). No evidence was captured for using predatory fish to control Ponto-Caspian gammarids (Action ID: 1087) or for using disease-causing organisms to control them (Action ID: 1090).

More broadly, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of using biological control to manage non-native, invasive or other problematic species populations on subtidal benthic invertebrate populations (Action ID: 2172) or marine and freshwater mammal populations (Action ID: 2852). While host-specific biological control using co-evolved herbivores has shown success in controlling some invasive plants like water primrose (Action ID: 1135), this approach has not been documented for invasive invertebrates like crayfish or gammarids.", "action_ids": ["1030", "1089", "1087", "1090", "2172", "2852", "1135"]}

